Durban - A northern KwaZulu-Natal step father, 35, is making his second appearance on Tuesday in the Kwangwanase Magistrate’s court in relation to the alleged rape of his 14-year-old step daughter. KZN police spokesperson Colonel Thembeka Mbhele said a 14-year-old female was allegedly raped by the suspect at her home in Zamazama and the matter was reported to the police. “A case of rape was opened at Emanguzi police station and transferred to Jozini Family Violence Child Protection and Sexual Offences Unit for investigation. Police arrested a 35-year-old suspect and he appeared in Kwangwanase Magistrates Court on 3 September 2019 and the matter was adjourned to 10 September 2019”. Speaking to Isolezwe on Sunday the teen’s mother said she had been in a relationship with the accused for two years and she did not suspect anything. She said she and accused had a child together. “When I asked my child about this she said it did not only happen once, so he was sleeping with me and her,” she said. Another man from Manguzi, Northern KZN, is also appearing in court charged with the rape of his 13-year-old niece. According to police on June 10 the teen was allegedly raped by a known suspect at her home in KwaGeorge area. A case of rape was opened at Emanguzi police station and transferred to Jozini Family Violence Child Protection and Sexual Offences Unit for investigation. Daily News